import EvmSmith.Framework

/-!
# The `Groth16` program — a one-public-input Groth16 verifier in raw EVM bytecode

A minimal analogue of the `verifyProof` function `snarkjs` emits for a Groth16
verifying key with **exactly one public input** (`nPublic = 1`). One entry
point:

| Solidity-shaped signature                                                  | Selector     |
|------------------------------------------------------------------------------|--------------|
| `verifyProof(uint256[2],uint256[2][2],uint256[2],uint256[1])` (view, bool)  | `0x43753b4d` |

`nPublic` is pinned to 1 *by construction* (not a missing feature): it lets
the calldata for `input` sit at a single fixed offset (`calldataload`), the
same trick `Demos/Weth` uses for its `uint256` argument — so no dynamic-array
ABI decoding or loop-carried accumulation is needed. Generalising to
`nPublic > 1` is exactly the gap called out in this demo's `Spec.lean`
docstring: a dynamic `uint256[]` decode plus a loop that accumulates
`Σ IC_i * input_i`, neither of which this framework has infrastructure for
yet.

Calldata layout (offsets are *after* the 4-byte selector):

```
4    proof.A.X
36   proof.A.Y
68   proof.B.X1   (the Fp2 "imaginary"/c1 component, EIP-197 ordering)
100  proof.B.X0
132  proof.B.Y1
164  proof.B.Y0
196  proof.C.X
228  proof.C.Y
260  input        (the single public input)
```

Behaviour: first, **`checkField`** — reject (via `revertLbl`) any `input ≥ r`
(the BN254 scalar-field modulus). This is not optional bookkeeping: `EC_MUL`
multiplies by a point of order `r`, so `(input + r)·P = input·P` for any `P`
on the curve — `input` and `input + k·r` are indistinguishable to the
pairing check. Without this guard, a caller could submit `input + r`
instead of the intended `input` and have it verify identically, while a
downstream consumer that uses the raw `uint256` calldata value (a nullifier,
a leaf, an amount, …) sees a different number. This mirrors `checkField` in
`circuit/verifier_reference.sol` (snarkjs's own generated verifier), which
guards the same way, though it returns `false` rather than reverting; this
contract reverts instead, for consistency with how it already handles the
three precompile-failure cases below (`BN_MUL`/`BN_ADD`/`SNARKV` failing all
share the same `revertLbl`, and the field check now does too).

Then: compute `vk_x = IC0 + IC1 * input` (one `BN_MUL` + one `BN_ADD`
precompile call), assemble the four-pair `ECPAIRING` input
`(-A, B), (alpha, beta), (vk_x, gamma), (C, delta)`, call the `SNARKV`
precompile (address `8`), and return its 32-byte boolean output verbatim. No
storage is ever touched — this is a `view` function from start to finish.

Memory map (bytes):

```
0x000–0x060  BN_MUL input:  IC1.x, IC1.y, input
0x060–0x0A0  BN_MUL output: vk_x_partial (= IC1 * input)
0x0A0–0x0E0  IC0 (written so that mem[0x060..0x0E0) = vk_x_partial ++ IC0,
             the 128-byte BN_ADD input — no copy needed)
0x100–0x140  pairing pair 0, G1: -A
0x140–0x1A0  pairing pair 0, G2: B            (from calldata)
0x1C0–0x200  pairing pair 1, G1: alpha
0x200–0x280  pairing pair 1, G2: beta
0x280–0x2C0  pairing pair 2, G1: vk_x         (BN_ADD writes its output here)
0x2C0–0x340  pairing pair 2, G2: gamma
0x340–0x380  pairing pair 3, G1: C            (from calldata)
0x380–0x400  pairing pair 3, G2: delta
0x400–0x420  SNARKV output (the 32-byte bool)
```

Assembly (PCs decimal; `IC0/IC1/alpha/beta/gamma/delta/Q/r` are 32-byte
immediates, elided below — see `assembly` for the full annotated listing):

```
pc   bytes                     mnemonic                comment
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
; Dispatch
0    60 00                     PUSH1 0x00
2    35                        CALLDATALOAD            selector word
3    60 e0                     PUSH1 0xe0
5    1c                        SHR
6    63 43 75 3b 4d            PUSH4 0x43753b4d        verifyProof selector
11   14                        EQ
12   61 00 15                  PUSH2 verifyLbl = 21
15   57                        JUMPI
16   60 00 60 00 fd            PUSH1 0; PUSH1 0; REVERT   no-match revert

; verifyProof (pc 21..897)
21   5b                        JUMPDEST                verifyLbl
22   7f<r> 61 01 04 35         PUSH32 r; PUSH2 260; CALLDATALOAD       input
58   10 15 61 03 82 57         LT; ISZERO; PUSH2 revertLbl=898; JUMPI  checkField
65   7f<IC1.x>   60 00 52       PUSH32 IC1x; PUSH1 0;   MSTORE
101  7f<IC1.y>   60 20 52       PUSH32 IC1y; PUSH1 32;  MSTORE
137  61 01 04 35 60 40 52      PUSH2 260; CALLDATALOAD; PUSH1 64; MSTORE   input
144  60 40 60 60 60 60 60 00   PUSH1 64,96,96,0
     60 00 60 07 5a f1         PUSH1 0,7; GAS; CALL        BN_MUL(IC1,input)
158  15 61 03 82 57            ISZERO; PUSH2 revertLbl=898; JUMPI
163  7f<IC0.x>   60 a0 52       PUSH32 IC0x; PUSH1 0xa0; MSTORE
199  7f<IC0.y>   60 c0 52       PUSH32 IC0y; PUSH1 0xc0; MSTORE
235  60 40 61 02 80 60 80       PUSH1 64; PUSH2 0x280; PUSH1 0x80
     60 60 60 00 60 06 5a f1   PUSH1 0x60,0,6; GAS; CALL   BN_ADD(part,IC0)
250  15 61 03 82 57            ISZERO; PUSH2 revertLbl; JUMPI
255  60 04 35 61 01 00 52      PUSH1 4; CALLDATALOAD; PUSH2 0x100; MSTORE   -A.x
262  60 24 35 80 15            PUSH1 0x24; CALLDATALOAD; DUP1; ISZERO
267  61 01 31 57                PUSH2 negDoneLbl=305; JUMPI
271  7f<Q> 03                  PUSH32 Q; SUB                negY = Q - A.y
305  5b 61 01 20 52            JUMPDEST negDoneLbl; PUSH2 0x120; MSTORE
310  ..                        4×(PUSH1 off; CALLDATALOAD; PUSH2 dst; MSTORE)  B
338  ..                        6×(PUSH32 const; PUSH2 dst; MSTORE)             alpha,beta
560  ..                        4×(PUSH32 const; PUSH2 dst; MSTORE)             gamma
708  ..                        2×(PUSH1 off; CALLDATALOAD; PUSH2 dst; MSTORE)  C
722  ..                        4×(PUSH32 const; PUSH2 dst; MSTORE)             delta
870  60 20 61 04 00 61 03 00   PUSH1 0x20; PUSH2 0x400; PUSH2 0x300
     61 01 00 60 00 60 08      PUSH2 0x100; PUSH1 0,8
     5a f1                     GAS; CALL                   SNARKV(4 pairs)
887  15 61 03 82 57            ISZERO; PUSH2 revertLbl; JUMPI
892  60 20 61 04 00 f3         PUSH1 0x20; PUSH2 0x400; RETURN   return the bool

; Revert (shared by checkField and the three failed-call branches)
898  5b 60 00 60 00 fd         JUMPDEST revertLbl; PUSH1 0; PUSH1 0; REVERT
```

Total: 904 bytes.

**The verifying-key constants below are real**, not placeholders: they are
`snarkjs zkey export verificationkey`'s output for the trivial circuit in
`circuit/square.circom` (`y = x*x`, one private input `x`, one public
output `y` — `nPublic = 1`, matching this contract's one-`input` layout).
Cross-checked against `circuit/verifier_reference.sol`, snarkjs's own
generated Solidity verifier for the same circuit, to pin down the
`ECPAIRING`/`SNARKV` `G2`-word ordering and the `-A` convention (this
contract's `negA` block computes the same value as the reference's
`mod(sub(q, A.y), q)`, just via an explicit `A.y = 0` branch instead of
relying on `MOD`'s wraparound). End-to-end-tested against a real proof in
`foundry/test/Groth16.t.sol` — see `circuit/` for how to regenerate the
circuit/proof if you change `square.circom`. -/

namespace EvmSmith.Groth16
open EvmYul EvmYul.EVM

/-! ## Selector -/

def verifySelector : UInt256 := UInt256.ofNat 0x43753b4d

/-! ## Control-flow destinations (absolute PCs) -/

def verifyLbl   : UInt256 := UInt256.ofNat 21
def negDoneLbl  : UInt256 := UInt256.ofNat 305
def revertLbl   : UInt256 := UInt256.ofNat 898

/-! ## Precompile addresses -/

def bnAddAddr  : AccountAddress := 6
def bnMulAddr  : AccountAddress := 7
def snarkvAddr : AccountAddress := 8

/-! ## The `alt_bn128` base-field modulus -/

def Q : UInt256 :=
  UInt256.ofNat 21888242871839275222246405745257275088696311157297823662689037894645226208583

/-! ## The `alt_bn128` scalar-field modulus (`checkField`'s bound)

A *different* prime from `Q` above: `r` is the order of the curve's prime
subgroup — the modulus public inputs live in, since they're field elements
in the circuit's scalar field, `Fr`. `Q` is the base field the curve's `x`/`y`
coordinates live in, `Fq`. Mixing the two up here would silently defeat
`checkField` (any `input < Q` would pass, including plenty of non-canonical
`input ≥ r`). -/

def r : UInt256 :=
  UInt256.ofNat 21888242871839275222246405745257275088548364400416034343698204186575808495617

